#Create new column with values 'weekday' and 'weekend'
# create a list of our conditions
conditions = [
    (df_allyear['day'] == 'Monday') | (df_allyear['day'] == 'Tuesday') | (df_allyear['day'] == 'Wednesday')
    | (df_allyear['day'] == 'Thursday') | (df_allyear['day'] == 'Friday'),
    (df_allyear['day']== 'Saturday') | (df_allyear['day'] == 'Sunday')
    ]

# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = ['Weekday', 'Weekend']

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
df_allyear['day_type'] = np.select(conditions, values)

# display updated DataFrame
df_allyear.sample(1)

    (df['day'] == 'Monday') | (df['day'] == 'Tuesday') | (df['day'] == 'Wednesday')

    (df['day']== 'Saturday') | (df['day'] == 'Sunday')

df['day_type'] = np.select(conditions, values)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The interest is in understanding the subscriber/users habits; when are most trips taken in terms of time of the day, day of the week and month of the year. Also, what variables affect the duration of their rides?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

It is expected that during week days, there are busy hours very well defined (before and after labour time, between 8 and 10 a.m and after 5 to 8 p.m.). I also believe that during Summer months, people tend to use more bycicles and thus, they use more this service. I am curious about if there is any tendency for a day of the week.

#creating a fuction that plots seaborn countplots
def Countplot(df, xvar, huevar=None, color=0, palette=None, order=None):
    #set plot dimentions
    plt.figure(figsize = [14,6])
    #plot
    sb.countplot(data=df, x=xvar, hue=huevar, color=sb.color_palette()[color], palette=palette, order=order, edgecolor='black')
    #clean up variable names
    xvar = xvar.replace("_"," ")
    if huevar:
        huevar = huevar.replace("_"," ")
    #add title and format it
    plt.title(f"Distribution of bike rides: {xvar} {'by' if huevar else ''} {huevar if huevar else ''}" .title(), fontsize=14)
    #add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel(xvar.title(), fontsize=10)
    #add y label and format it
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=10)

Conclusions¶

In the first part of this document 2 different dataframes were developed: one that only includes trip data for the month of February 2019, and other that includes trip data for all the months of 2019. The original given data for February 2019 includes more variables than the rest of the data for the other months. So, having these 2 datasets available enabled a more broaden research about the time variables computed, such as the months of the year and the effect they have in the users behaviors.

The second part consisted in exploring the variables available in the 2 datasets via univariate, bivariate and multivariate visualizations. It was possible to find inconsistencies in the data and possible relationships between them.

The distributions of member ages and the trips duration are right-skewed, meaning that most of the users are young (ages between 25 and 40 years-old) and use this bike sharing system to make short rides (8 to 15 min). The distribution of rides along the weekdays hours is bimodal: the two peaks are during the busy hours. On the other hand, the rides along the hours of a weekend day follows a normal distribution. Also, it was possible to notice that this system is used more on weekdays than during weekends.

Finally, it was possible to notice that the age does not have a linear influence on the duration of trips; the members gender does not influence the trip duration; on the contrary, the type of user and the time (time of the year and type of day, week/weekend) has impact on the average of the duration of trips.
